    <Folder>
      <name>Intelligence Summary</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>AI Council Assessment</name>
        <styleUrl>#intel</styleUrl>
        <description>The synthesized intelligence assessment reveals a globally distributed but highly concentrated US military posture, with particular emphasis on countering near-peer threats in the Indo-Pacific and Middle East. The Western Pacific remains the primary flashpoint, with multiple carrier strike groups (USS Nimitz, Carl Vinson, John C. Stennis, Theodore Roosevelt, Abraham Lincoln) and amphibious ready groups (USS America, Wasp, Makin Island, Essex, Boxer, Bonhomme Richard, Kearsarge, Bataan, Tripoli) deployed to the Philippine Sea, South China Sea, and East China Sea. These deployments are directly aligned with countering Chinese maritime assertiveness, supporting freedom of navigation operations, and reinforcing allied security commitments in Japan, South Korea, and the Philippines. The Arabian Gulf and Strait of Hormuz continue to be critical operational areas, with USS Gerald R. Ford and USS Dwight D. Eisenhower conducting patrols to deter Iranian threats and ensure maritime security. The Mediterranean hosts USS Harry S. Truman, supporting NATO operations amid ongoing Russian naval activity in the Black Sea. Aircraft data indicates robust ISR and transport missions, with high-altitude surveillance flights over the Aegean, Sea of Japan, and Eastern Mediterranean monitoring Russian and regional adversary activities. Training missions in Europe and the Pacific underscore the US commitment to allied exercises and readiness. The overall posture reflects a deliberate strategy of global power projection, rapid deployment capability, and crisis response, with particular focus on deterring aggression in key theaters while maintaining flexibility for global contingencies.</description>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>0,0,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
    </Folder>
